162
00:30:08.085 --> 00:30:13.635
Incoming livestream: Good morning, everyone. I'm Raghini Ramalingam, and I lead the enterprise security team at Snowflake.


163
00:30:14.015 --> 00:30:25.025
Incoming livestream: I wanted to thank Gaddy and the team at Gnostic for putting this conference together, and all of you for this great community that has come together, to discuss the challenges that we have.


164
00:30:25.235 --> 00:30:26.784
Incoming livestream: in AI security.


165
00:30:29.325 --> 00:30:32.954
Incoming livestream: I want to start off by making a quick observation.


166
00:30:33.185 --> 00:30:43.895
Incoming livestream: Enterprise security, for decades, assumed that the execution in the enterprise is predefined or deterministic.


167
00:30:44.525 --> 00:30:48.304
Incoming livestream: So, we had identities authenticating, we had…


168
00:30:48.605 --> 00:30:52.605
Incoming livestream: You know, systems and workflows executing predefined logic.


169
00:30:52.945 --> 00:31:00.184
Incoming livestream: And automation existed, but that was based on what humans defined, and systems just executed it.


170
00:31:00.395 --> 00:31:04.005
Incoming livestream: And today, AI, it's fundamentally different.


171
00:31:05.035 --> 00:31:09.724
Incoming livestream: We are deploying systems that now make decisions at runtime.


172
00:31:10.155 --> 00:31:15.564
Incoming livestream: and invoke actions from the endpoint to the cloud to SaaS.


173
00:31:15.915 --> 00:31:21.254
Incoming livestream: And, and blurring boundaries. And this is basically moved from


174
00:31:22.115 --> 00:31:30.555
Incoming livestream: Deterministic action to making context-aware actions in real time that are not controlled by humans.


175
00:31:31.655 --> 00:31:34.314
Incoming livestream: So, how do we govern?


176
00:31:34.585 --> 00:31:37.174
Incoming livestream: This new ecosystem.


177
00:31:38.155 --> 00:31:46.294
Incoming livestream: The traditional governance models don't work anymore, and governance has to become dynamic and evolve.


178
00:31:46.755 --> 00:32:00.054
Incoming livestream: I'd like to quote our CISO, Brad Jones, who said, governing AI at a company like Snowflake, we are the AI data cloud, is like laying tracks in front of a running train.


179
00:32:00.645 --> 00:32:05.454
Incoming livestream: And our challenge was to lay those tracks


180
00:32:05.965 --> 00:32:08.594
Incoming livestream: And not slow down the running train.


181
00:32:09.285 --> 00:32:13.805
Incoming livestream: How do you achieve that? So we had to come up with a governance model, that…


182
00:32:14.555 --> 00:32:17.705
Incoming livestream: You know, helped us to make decisions really quickly.


183
00:32:17.875 --> 00:32:26.335
Incoming livestream: and enable innovation, but safely and securely. So I'll walk you through the governance model we adopted to enable this.


184
00:32:29.545 --> 00:32:34.225
Incoming livestream: So why is AI governance fundamentally different?


185
00:32:34.645 --> 00:32:38.045
Incoming livestream: First, AI tool adoption does not wait


186
00:32:38.235 --> 00:32:42.275
Incoming livestream: for review cycles. And it does not follow the pace that


187
00:32:42.435 --> 00:33:00.114
Incoming livestream: you know, that we see in the traditional enterprises. It begins with engineers experimenting, with product teams trying to integrate, with solution engineers trying to showcase, and business teams trying to increase their productivity using AI.


188
00:33:00.555 --> 00:33:05.854
Incoming livestream: So we had to come up with processes that evolved at that speed.


189
00:33:06.365 --> 00:33:07.845
Incoming livestream: Feature velocity.


190
00:33:08.085 --> 00:33:16.144
Incoming livestream: And second, feature velocity outpaces, you know, any kind of feature releases. AI vendors are releasing features


191
00:33:16.715 --> 00:33:22.954
Incoming livestream: Weekly, and sometimes few times a week. And therefore, our security processes had to become dynamic.


192
00:33:23.405 --> 00:33:41.285
Incoming livestream: Third, most importantly, AI builds the boundary. We used to have, you know, control planes that were strictly dedicated to endpoint, or network, or cloud, or SaaS, and today, with AI, one prompt can trigger an action at an endpoint.


193
00:33:41.645 --> 00:33:54.774
Incoming livestream: It can read… make system calls, read or write files on the endpoint, it can make outbound network egress, or it can invoke APIs reaching out to SaaS platforms.


194
00:33:54.775 --> 00:34:02.685
Incoming livestream: And therefore, the control plane has to be across all of these domains, and cannot be just static control planes.


195
00:34:03.155 --> 00:34:08.155
Incoming livestream: The risk, again, is, once again, is no longer static, because the execution model has now


196
00:34:08.865 --> 00:34:13.645
Incoming livestream: Turned from one of deterministic to non-deterministic.


197
00:34:14.075 --> 00:34:30.675
Incoming livestream: And the execution boundary has significantly expanded. And therefore, in order to be able to govern this AI, we need to evolve our governance model at the same velocity at which the technology is evolving.


198
00:34:33.635 --> 00:34:37.034
Incoming livestream: So we realized early that in order to make


199
00:34:37.725 --> 00:34:44.824
Incoming livestream: You know, in order to be… our governance model to be dynamic, we needed to have a structure that


200
00:34:45.355 --> 00:34:48.085
Incoming livestream: Allowed us to make quick decisions.


201
00:34:48.385 --> 00:34:51.595
Incoming livestream: So we formed an enterprise steering committee with


202
00:34:51.805 --> 00:34:59.784
Incoming livestream: with the, you know, members from security, IT, legal, privacy, AI, ML, data engineering, and procurement teams.


203
00:35:00.065 --> 00:35:14.674
Incoming livestream: And we… with… and all of these members came together because they had the ability to see the AI adoption across the enterprise and AI usage patterns, and so with those, we…


204
00:35:14.905 --> 00:35:23.574
Incoming livestream: Identified the risks that we saw across these usage patterns and adoption, and we came up with mediation controls.


205
00:35:23.765 --> 00:35:29.185
Incoming livestream: And whether it be technical controls, process controls, or contractual protections.


206
00:35:29.805 --> 00:35:35.254
Incoming livestream: And then, as a next step, we bubbled that up to our executive leadership teams.


207
00:35:35.485 --> 00:35:46.945
Incoming livestream: and in engineering, product management, sales, customer experience, IT, etc. And these are the teams that were innovating at speed with the AI technology.


208
00:35:47.025 --> 00:36:01.634
Incoming livestream: And so this helped us to surface the risk up to the executive leadership and make risk-informed decisions that align with our leadership's risk appetite. Because at Snowflake.


209
00:36:02.465 --> 00:36:09.865
Incoming livestream: you know, engineering innovation is… and engineering at speed is in our DNA.


210
00:36:10.015 --> 00:36:17.295
Incoming livestream: And… enabling or disabling AI was not a security decision.


211
00:36:17.495 --> 00:36:33.294
Incoming livestream: it is actually a business decision, and it's not a security trade-off, it's a business trade-off. So having our executive leadership weigh in, and making decisions aligned with the risk appetite of the business.


212
00:36:33.855 --> 00:36:36.705
Incoming livestream: Helped us actually get that alignment.


213
00:36:36.835 --> 00:36:40.925
Incoming livestream: As well as any cultural change that was required in the environment.


214
00:36:42.065 --> 00:36:52.964
Incoming livestream: So we shifted from reactive approvals to proactive risk ownership, and truly, this structure was the one that helped us make decisions much faster.


215
00:36:55.615 --> 00:36:59.205
Incoming livestream: You cannot govern what you cannot see, so it's…


216
00:36:59.605 --> 00:37:19.344
Incoming livestream: Getting visibility into enterprise AI usage and adoption is critical in order to be able to govern. So, we looked at four pathways in order to get visibility. First is our procurement process, and we already had a pretty mature process, and we built AI oversight into that.


217
00:37:19.495 --> 00:37:28.134
Incoming livestream: And we looked at, we looked… we rationalized the products, not based on features.


218
00:37:28.245 --> 00:37:42.825
Incoming livestream: And we not only did a security risk review, but we also looked at whether the tool had redundant capabilities. So what that helped us do is eliminate tools which had overlapping capabilities.


219
00:37:42.885 --> 00:37:48.694
Incoming livestream: And, which not only just reduced our, operational overhead, but also


220
00:37:48.785 --> 00:37:52.004
Incoming livestream: Helped us eliminate unnecessary attack surfaces.


221
00:37:53.255 --> 00:38:12.524
Incoming livestream: Next, we, we all know that AI does not come just in a new product, it is turning on AI features in existing products, so we gated those, turning on new features through security reviews. We required people to go through security reviews in order to enable AI features in existing tools and platforms.


222
00:38:12.945 --> 00:38:21.634
Incoming livestream: And, third, most importantly, we actually did an active discovery for AI artifacts and interactions across the enterprise.


223
00:38:21.905 --> 00:38:33.535
Incoming livestream: And being the AI data cloud, our security lake lives in our own platform, and with the AI capabilities that we have on our platform, we were able to quickly get insights.


224
00:38:33.715 --> 00:38:39.945
Incoming livestream: Based on the telemetry that we had on the endpoint data, network,


225
00:38:40.345 --> 00:38:50.974
Incoming livestream: cloud and SaaS environments, we were able to identify AI artifacts, such as MCP components, models, agents, and those interactions.


226
00:38:52.175 --> 00:38:54.915
Incoming livestream: Last but not the least, we…


227
00:38:55.515 --> 00:39:01.735
Incoming livestream: Constantly partnered and had discussions with our peers in the business units.


228
00:39:01.825 --> 00:39:18.354
Incoming livestream: And this is critical. You need to have security partners in all business units that you, you know, you keep in touch with, so you're aware of getting early insights into AI adoption in those business units, and that helps us make informed decisions.


229
00:39:21.065 --> 00:39:32.655
Incoming livestream: So with that visibility and that governance structure, we were actually able to effect a cultural change when we were able to enable AI adoption responsibly.


230
00:39:33.575 --> 00:39:34.765
Incoming livestream: So first, we…


231
00:39:34.985 --> 00:39:45.474
Incoming livestream: established enterprise guardrails, so we, you know, deployed endpoint, network, and DLP controls that were aligned to AI usage patterns.


232
00:39:46.035 --> 00:39:49.575
Incoming livestream: And the goal here was simple, just allowed, approved.


233
00:39:49.755 --> 00:39:55.094
Incoming livestream: Use cases and approved tools, and then maintain consistent enforcement.


234
00:39:55.335 --> 00:40:11.864
Incoming livestream: Then we, with the visibility that we had, we basically, identified tools that were broadly used in the organization and made a conscious decision to procure some of those tools so that we can, manage them effectively.


235
00:40:12.095 --> 00:40:17.304
Incoming livestream: And in some cases, we decided that some of the tools were risky, and


236
00:40:17.575 --> 00:40:23.325
Incoming livestream: And, you know, guided our users towards approved alternatives in the enterprise.


237
00:40:24.875 --> 00:40:25.775
Incoming livestream: And last…


238
00:40:25.935 --> 00:40:35.995
Incoming livestream: Lastly, we had, and again, Snowflake is, is a place where, there is a lot of AI experimentation happening.


239
00:40:36.115 --> 00:40:52.284
Incoming livestream: And so, when we needed to provide… when AI experimentation needed to happen, we resorted… our core operating principle was provide isolated environments with test tenants and synthetic data, and where that was not possible.


